United States: Repetition Is Mother of Wisdom
He even becomes comical, the steady effort with which Barack Obama, president of the reputation as wise, replicates his predecessor's strategy on the Afghan issue, which he himself considered to be very simple.
When he ended up letting his doctrine sweat so ardently awaited, it turned out that he had copied it to carbon paper since Bush's Iraqi scenario three years ago.
Not content to use in the text even several times the expression "as in Iraq", he did not hesitate, moreover, to use the title of the Bush speech of January 2007 as the title of his own speech: "A new road forward"
At the same time, he personally criticized Bush's idea of sending new reinforcements to an Iraq consumed by the civil war as being "irresponsible and a catastrophic decision in its consequences."
The following months, however, showed that Bush's strategy, which emanated from the recommendations of campaign commanders, was the only one possible and likely to succeed to such an extent that the newspapers at present do not speak at all about Iraq.
This did not improve Bush's reputation, but, objectively speaking, he left his successor a much more favourable final situation than one could expect.
Barack Obama hopes that in Afghanistan, the miracle will happen again
It was again the campaign commanders who called for an increase in the military contingent, including the commander of the Afghan operation, General Stanley McCristal, who even severely criticized the White House's reluctance despite the habit of subordination.
He asked for 40,000 men in order to make the situation more favourable.
The president hesitated for three months, but in the absence of a better option, he at least swindled the general of 10,000 soldiers.
He managed to remove the promise of an additional 5,000 from Europe, even though he originally had 10,000.
What brings the most problems throughout Obama's strategy seems to be his intention to withdraw the armies from Afghanistan within 18 months and to complete this whole process within three years. Obama's entire doctrine brings more questions than it provides answers.
Many doubt that an increase of half will bear the same fruit as the increase in Iraq.
Despite the fratricidal wars of recent years, Iraqi society is relatively well organized and its leaders honour the agreements.
The Afghan situation stands out in the exact opposite - no one can be counted on and no treaty is respected.
In these circumstances, it is difficult to prepare Afghan security forces, accustomed to changing their leadership day by day according to their arrangements.
Political institutions, although officially founded, will remain only powder in the eyes behind which patriarchal ethnic relations will proliferate.
It is particularly complex to balance the interests of the various ethnic groups in view of the lack of clarity about the relationship, which is still complicated by Pakistani and Iranian influences.
Even the foundation of a "state that is prompt to act", which is the basic purpose of the operation, does not seem to be very real.
The time horizon of Obama's strategy is perplexed by his voluntarism.
In the past eight years, the situation in Afghanistan has only worsened and is currently on the brink of chaos.
Only a purely romantic and out of reality heart can be persuaded that the little soldiers sent into the tumult of war for their "quick return home" will bring a true miracle.
From a political point of view, setting a date for the withdrawal of troops is purely irresponsible as the Taliban will regard it as the indirect admission of the American defeat.
The latest NATO summit has shown that the will of Europeans to participate in military operations in Afghanistan is turning to the negative.
European policies do not know or want to explain to their voters how security in Germany or Italy is linked to a war in the mountains of the Hindu Kush.
Another factor capable of radically altering the situation is the evolution of events related to Iran.
If the situation continues to deteriorate and the enhanced sanctions have no effect on the Iranians, the Americans will find themselves faced with the very difficult question of resolving the problem through the use of military force.
It will have to be answered, for example, when, according to Obama, America will come to the victorious withdrawal of troops from Afghanistan.
However, each solution of this kind will lead to a dramatic reversal of the Afghan situation.
The only trick for Obama is the fact that there are three years left until the presidential elections and therefore there is still enough time for him to come up with a new strategy, in case it turns out to be a total fiasco.
