Czech discovery: a substance that works on "endurant" HIV viruses too
A team of Czech and German scientists are testing new combinations that can slow the spread of HIV in the body.
The main advantage of the improved substance is that it also acts on viruses that have already developed immunity to drugs.
This reality takes precedence in some cases over the fact that the combination does not act as intensively on the common variants of the virus as well as some medicines already available.
It is not possible to cure AIDS at this time.
However, the life of the sick can be radically prolonged through a mixture of medicines that prevent the growth of HIV virus in the body.
However, their consumption has a number of side effects.
Moreover, the suppression of this multiplication has the effect of developing what are called resistant viruses on which drugs no longer have effect.
The work of experts from three institutions, the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic, the VŠCHT of Prague and the University of Heidelberg, paves the way for a way to cope with the resistance of the virus.
They have shown that substances called metalocarboranes act on the protein responsible for the multiplication of the HIV virus.
Metalocarboranes are an assembly of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
This combination blocks the development of the virus in a different way from all the drugs used so far and that is why they could overcome the problem of resistance.
The researchers' work leads them to discover new "improved" substances, based on their knowledge of the molecular mechanics of their bonds on the proteins of the virus.
Metalocarboranes have a unique three-dimensional structure: two multi-walled cages are formed by the boron, hydrogen and carbon atoms and connected by a metal atom, in this case the cobalt.
A traitoric and resistant virus.
HIV protease is a protein of the HIV virus that is essential to the life cycle of the virus.
Without the division of the HIV virus caused by HIV protease there would be no birth of mature infectious particles of the virus.
