The UN-sponsored climate conference -- characterized so far by disorganized assignments and mutual recriminations -- has returned to the spotlight on the ramp on Friday, due to the publication of a document highlighting ambitious greenhouse gas reductions over the next 40 years, with industrialized nations supporting most of the burden, in the next 40 years.
The text that could provide the basis for a final political agreement to regulate greenhouse gases highlighted the remaining obstacles, as much as it shed light on the way forward.
But it has been seen as an important step forward in the negotiations that are running out of time, with more than 100 leaders from all over the world arriving next week in Copenhagen.
Drafted by a United Nations ad hoc working group, the text does not say how rich countries would give to the poor to support global warming, both in the short and long term.
And it offers a wide range of options for key issues, including how developed and emerging new economies could reduce their carbon production and what would be the upper limit of the global temperature increase that those responsible would be willing to tolerate.
It gives great flexibility to the process, said John Coequyt, Representative of the Sierra Club in Washington.
Michael Zammit Cutajar, who wrote six pages of the document, studied a 180-page negotiating text to focus on what the Executive Secretary-General on climate change of the United Nations, Yvo de Boer, described as "the complete picture".
It shows the guidelines for a possible agreement in which industrial nations would collectively reduce their emissions by 25 to 45 per cent compared to 1990 levels in 2020, while the major developing countries, during the same period, would reduce their emissions by 15 to 30 per cent.
Together, countries would reduce emissions by between 50 and 95 per cent by 2050.
The European Union has also relaunched negotiations on Friday, promising to provide $3.6 billion a year over the next three years to help the poorest countries adapt to the impact of climate change -- to cope with floods and drought or to avoid deforestation.
However, on Friday, the same verbal altercations took place, which dominated the negotiations since last week.
Todd Stern, United States Representative for Climate Negotiation, rejected any discussion that required the reduction of greenhouse gases by industrialized countries, in comparison with the voluntary efforts made by major emerging economies, if they were not financed by developed countries.
This change is the signal that the Obama administration becomes tougher towards China than the Bush administration was two years ago.
The United States will not sign an agreement without the efforts and actions of the major developing countries, says Stern, who also regretted that the text does not insist enough to ensure that the reductions could be verified by external observers.
Stern made his comments an hour after the Chinese Deputy Foreign Minister, He Yafei said that the U.S. prime negotiator, either lacked "good sense," or was "extremely irresponsible" for saying earlier this week that the U.S. would not financially help China to fight global warming.
With the future economic trajectories of the major world powers at stake, defects have emerged both within the third world and between the industrial world and emerging economies.
The current battle concerns more the rescue of individual economies than the rescue of the planet, with China and the United States arguing about their respective obligations while the poorest nations insist that the two dozen most influential countries ignore the scientific imperatives of acting more courageously.
Ricardo Ulate, a delegate from Costa Rica, said that it was not surprising that the major powers were fighting to know who should bear the costs of reducing greenhouse gases, even though vulnerable countries had become more aggressive in their attempt to hold large emitters accountable for their actions.
It is really a game in which a new economic hegemony is developed, said Ulate, who is also Climate Advisor for Mexico and Central America for International Conservation.
Some of these countries more vulnerable to the impact of climate change have indicated that they will continue to put pressure on a legally binding treaty in Copenhagen, although most key participants say that the negotiations will lead to a minimum political agreement.
The Alliance of Small Island States, which brings together 43 members, drafted a 24-page draft treaty, early Friday morning.
Artur Runge-Metzger, Head of the European Commission's Climate Unit, said that the action of small island states "has put political pressure on the complete political process", in part by what they are now unified and asking emerging economies such as China and India to act.
Discussions became an urgent matter, while delegates focused on the fact that they had to resolve most of the outstanding issues before the heads of governments reached an agreement.
