A managerial revolution or an end to economic intelligence?
If nothing changes in the governance of large French companies, our struggle for the development of economic intelligence will have been in vain...
For more than ten years, the attitude of management of large companies towards its employees has been reminiscent of the position of companies vis-à-vis consumers prior to the marketing revolution: it is a question of making employees adhere to "values" determined from above as they used to be, of imposing on consumers products designed by factory technicians.
By putting the customer at the heart of the company, the marketing revolution has put the strategies of conquering the markets in place... although the authoritarian temptation to impose products disconnected from customer preference factors comes back on a regular basis!
Demobilization of employees can lead to mortifying demoralization.
Suicides in France Telecom, PSA or Renault are only the emerging part of a much more general phenomenon that affects managers in particular.
This demobilization seriously undermines the development of all the intellectual functions of the enterprise, including R&D and, more importantly, economic intelligence.
Indeed, EI "requires all stakeholders (...) a proactive approach and a forward-looking vision"; it requires employees to commit that authoritarian management revenue totally contradicts.
That is why we call for a managerial revolution that would involve putting employees at the centre of the company's concerns in the same way as the customer.
The very relative usefulness of internal opinion surveys
Will internal opinion surveys – like Orange's questionnaire to its employees – encourage this revolution in managerial practices?
Unfortunately, I'm afraid not.
- First of all because I was able to see that, in the face of a new situation, any structure finally manages, after many detours, to do first... what it has always done.!
- Then, because authoritarianism – one of the pathologies of power – grows proportionally to the importance of its own failures.
- Finally, because most leaders have a simplistic vision of human behavior.
From the great engineering schools, they have a mechanistic interpretation of psychology.
They adopt, through intellectual comfort, the old Behaviorist theory, recently reactivated by the US "neurosciences" and widely disseminated, without their knowledge, by the institutes of studies and the media.
Thus, by suggesting that it is possible to handle the "levers" (sic) of the commitment of the executives, a recent survey by Ipsos published in Le Figaro.fr comforts the leaders in a position of mechanistic governance, unsuitable for the world today.
Identifying and measuring mobilization factors
On the contrary, the managerial revolution necessary for the proper functioning of modern enterprises presupposes adopting a finalist vision of human behavior.
It consists of incorporating, in any reasoning or practice of governance, a fundamental observation: for employees, commitment to the company is only possible if it appears clearly as a means of realizing part of their dreams, their ambitions, their projects.
Currently, only studies from the Motifunctional Analysis adopt this conception of employee motivations.
These studies have shown that they judge their company on the basis of a predetermined doxa that allows them, through their perceived image of the company, to evaluate what it offers them to carry out their life projects.
Through the identification and measurement of these mobilization factors, business leaders can control, anticipate and anticipate their "social performance" and return their human resources management "to the place".
They thus create a ground for the concerted development of robust and efficient economic intelligence.
