The cradle of dinosaurs
The Tawa found resembled the other carnivorous dinosaurs: this biped was about 2 meters long by 1.50m high, its hind limbs were powerful, its elongated skull was equipped with sharp and curved teeth, its short arms ended up with faucille claws and it had a long tail.
If this species had lived a few million years later, it would have had nothing exceptional.
But, as reported by Sertling Nesbitt of the University of Texas in Austin and his colleagues in Thursday's Science magazine, the Tawa trovae is one of the first dinosaurs with these morphological characteristics.
This animal lived 215 million years ago in New Mexico, which at that time was part of the land that emerged from the supercontinent, the Panggea and was to the equator.
Sertling Nesbitt says that the discovery of the Tawa sheds light on the evolution of the first dinosaurs.
Indeed, he provides us with information on the relationship, distribution and characteristics of the latter.
It was in 2006 that Sertling Nesbitt began excavations with other paleontologists at the Gohst Ranch site north of New Mexico.
Randall Irmis of the Museum of Natural History of Utah and member of the excavation team tells that sometimes they found a dozen bones in one day, which is absolutely unique for a sedimentary layer dating from the Trias.
Scientists soon realized that some of these bones belonged to a new species.
The excavations have updated the remains of five specimens.
A discovery that confirms theories about the beginnings of dinosaur evolution.
The researchers named him Tawa according to the word of the Hopi Indians for the sun god.
For Sterling Nesbitt, this is a very exceptional discovery: dinosaur fossils from the Trias are extremely rare and are limited to a few incomplete bone fragments.
Not all paleontology experts share this enthusiasm.
For example, Martin Sander of the University of Bonn does not find this discovery to be particularly spectacular, but he points out that it can confirm certain theories regarding the beginnings of dinosaur evolution.
According to the current state of knowledge, dinosaurs appeared on Earth about 230 million years ago.
Most of the oldest fossils, however, are fragmented and incomplete, making it very difficult to classify the very first dinosaurs.
The experts wonder, among other things, at what time the Saurians divided into three major evolutionary groups: the theropods (carnivores) that include the tyrannosaurus and the velociraptor that appeared later and from which the birds, the sauropods, quadrupeds along the neck, and those related to them and the Ornithischian herbivores of which the species such as the triceratops and the stegosaurus belong.
According to studies by S. Nesbitt and his colleagues, the Tawa is one of the first theropods.
This species presents an interesting report of both primitive and developed characteristics, said S. Nesbitt.
Researchers have found evidence that Tawa found small air bags in her bones at the skull level, as did birds that are descendants of the theropods.
These small pockets of air make it easier for birds to breathe in relation to mammals.
It appears that the vertebrae were also partially filled with air in Tawa found.
According to Randall Irmis, the Tawa is one of the oldest theropods with small air bags in their bones.
As the related lineage of the huge sauropods also had air bags and a light frame, it may be thought that their common ancestor already had this beneficial innovation.
Three successive waves of migration to North America.
As the most primitive dinosaurs known to live in South America, the researchers concluded that the saurians had appeared there.
As a result, the three major lines of evolution have divided and spread from South America to the rest of the world, that is, all the lands that emerged that formed the Pangee supercontinent.
This seems to be confirmed by the fact that the team of paleontologists also discovered the remains of two other theropods that are not particularly related to it.
The three species cannot descend from a common ancestor who would have migrated, the researchers say.
Alan Turner of the Museum of Natural History in New York and co-author of Science Studies magazine said there would have been at least three waves of migration to North America.
There are, of course, some contradictions.
Martin Sander, a paleontologist in Bonn, says that there is an even older species, the silesaura, which lived in present-day Poland and belongs to a group related to dinosaurs.
According to him, this could give an erroneous view because there are many fossil dinosaurs in South America that have been preserved while there are virtually none on other continents.
On the other hand, how did dinosaurs manage to become the dominant tetrapods of the secondary era when they came from a relatively rare collateral line of the reptile branch, still remains a mystery today.
At the time of the Trias, dinosaurs shared their habitat with many other reptiles, such as the ancestors of current crocodiles and with many other Saurians.
Towards the end of the Trias the dinosaurs spread throughout the planet thus promoting the development of many new species while others, who were related to them, disappeared between the Trias and the Jurassic.
Such success, however, is not eternal.
To explain this transformation, Martin Sander sees two hypotheses.
There may have been a massive extinction that dinosaurs have survived randomly while other reptiles have disappeared.
Or the dinosaurs were better suited and therefore they were able to eliminate competition on the ground.
In any case, such success is not eternal.
150 million years later, the fall of a meteorite favored the development of a group of animals that had also developed during the Trias and that since that time had been in the shadows: they were mammals.
