For ten years, Kasten has been collecting reports on hallucinations and illusory image phenomena: last year he published his results in a book entitled "The Unreal World in Our Head".
Hallucinations are well part of the concomitant phenomena typical of psychosis but also of an impressive number of other pathologies.
These include mental disorders such as borderline or depression, but also migraine, epilepsy, multiple sclerosis, Alzheimer's disease, or head trauma.
It is surprising that under certain conditions even the brain of healthy people is subject to hallucinations.
Hallucinations, according to Kasten, consist of fragments of memories that are normally inhibited.
They take shape when the areas of the brain that treat sensory perceptions, are hyperactive or not sufficiently restrained; when our brain warms up but also when there is no stimulation.
Drugs can trigger this condition as well as brain injury or psychosis.
But also the lack of stimuli, stress, sorrows of love or other exceptional mental states.
In recent studies, one third of participants acknowledged having experienced hallucinations at least once in their lives.
In the summer of 2005 Sarah K. was 16, she lived in a small town in Mecklenburg-Pomerania before and went to high school.
A young girl who's making it all normal to tell you the truth.
If there weren't the pictures and the voices.
During recreation, a young boy, thin, with long brown hair, sometimes speaks to him.
When she answers her comrades look at her, surprised – no one else sees or hears this boy.
They think this shy girl is a lunatic dreamer, but Sarah K doesn't dream, she's sure.
She is awake, hears and sees this boy just as she sees and hears the girl sitting next to her on the bench.
She can even perceive his presence momentarily.
It's a nice feeling, she finds this young man nice.
Am I crazy, she sometimes asks.
But she knows that this young man and the other visions are not real and that they will disappear again.
At night the apparitions are, in general, frightening.
Often the visions are heavy.
When she is in class, she may not be able to take the course because the teacher is just presenting a new student in her eyes and ears while he is invisible to others and the teacher is obviously explaining equations in the picture.
At night the apparitions are, in general, frightening.
When, in the darkness of her room, she waits for the sleep that comes too rarely and too late, she can often not make the distinction if she is awake or dream already, if the images she sees, the grinning faces or the girl with bloody cuts on her arms and legs are in front of her eyes open or closed.
Leave me alone, she cries out to these creatures.
She doesn't talk to her parents or friends, they'd think she was crazy.
Fall 2009. Sarah K. is now 20 years old.
She graduated last year and lives with her friend.
A year ago, the hallucinations stopped.
Since she's been online with psychologist Kasten, she knows very well that she's not crazy.
Madness is also a work of art of despair.
When someone is socially isolated or does not have enough stimulation, the likelihood is high that they will have hallucinations after some time.
I guess the brain isn't busy enough, so there's animation.
Sarah K., the only girl, was afraid of other children when she was little and often played alone.
Her hallucinations began when she learned at the age of 13, that the man she called Dad, since she was of thinking age, was not her real father.
These are the same brain zones that are active for visual and acoustic hallucinations, and for real impressions and noises, it is therefore very difficult for people like Sarah K to make the difference between illusion and reality. "Every experience," according to Kasten "takes place in the brain, reality is formed from there.
Hallucinations are also images that form in the brain, which is why they seem so real."
For Kasten, night dreams are also a form of hallucination.
Hallucinations of healthy people are not fundamentally distinct from those of acute psychosis.
Unlike schizophrenia, the mentally healthy person is able to recognize that fantasies are not real images.
That's why Kasten advises his patients to cherish hallucinations as a particular talent.
There's only one step between dream and hallucination.
In our world too focused on consciousness, unfortunately, we tend to take imaginary experiences for pathologies, according to Michael Schmidt-Degenhard, professor at Heidelberg and chief physician at the Psychiatry and Psychotherapy Clinic at Florence Nightingale Hospital in Düsseldorf.
Psychosis is a serious, painful disease but also contains something positive, creative - madness is a work of art of despair.
Schmidt-Degenhard studied the so-called oniroid experience form, a particular form of dream-awakened consciousness modification.
Oniroid experiences are very complex semi-dreams that are perceived as real by the one who lives them and that it cannot differentiate from dream even when it is awake.
The oniroid state of consciousness occurs during trauma or in situations of extreme diseases as for patients with fully conscious polyradiculopathy, experience motor paralysis.
According to Schmidt-Degenhard, when a human being is threatened by a loss of self and the world, due to a total and lasting inability to move, he replaces this real situation that affects his life, with his own imaginary world that is dissociated from reality.
It's a state of mind between dream and hallucination.
Since it is not possible to overcome the situation in reality, a change of world takes place but the real situation is represented in the imagination.
It is, in fact, an intense form of means and interpretation, in an intolerable situation in itself, an organizational capacity that is given to us, men, not to sink into the void of the loss of consciousness.
Everything is real even later in memories.
Zurich's Peter Cornelius Classen, an art historian, also describes his oniroid experiences in his book "Changing the Heart" as an action to save the soul.
He is 49 years old, when his conscious is leaving for a trip several days after the operation of a heart valve followed by a transplant; during this time, his body is condemned to remain motionless in resuscitation.
Claussen dives into a world he created from every room, visits foreign places, travels through time . He sees himself as an old man tied up in a railway sanatorium, a robot at his bedside looking after his health.
He lives in the middle ages among nobles who make blood-based narcotics.
He is kidnapped by a Greek on a motorcycle who takes him to his country, surfs with his hospital bed in the snowshoe of the Alps and meets a Korean mobster.
He absorbs himself completely into this imaginary world, everything is real even later in his memories.
According to Claussen, these inner journeys are fundamentally different from any dream.
The dream is a completely different state, he writes describing what he has experienced.
Unlike dreams, memories from mental travel are extremely clear and very detailed even years later.
It can even be said that they are much more distinct and more intense than actual experience.
The intensity of this experience breaks the horizon of our other daily experiences, according to psychiatrist Schmidt-Degenhard.
In short, the oniroid delusions, psychosis, hallucinations and psychedelic experiences show us how fragile our inner representations of external reality are even in a state of alertness.
Any change in the state of consciousness, summarizes psychologist Kasten "can cause a distortion of what we call reality."
An experience that can also be quite enriching.
