75% of working mothers have had occupational problems because of their motherhood
Discrimination at work has increased in recent years, especially for women of young generations who want to be mothers.
This is revealed by the study "Fecundity and professional career of women in Spain", carried out by CSIC in collaboration with the Institute of Women.
The survey of 9,737 women between the ages of 15 and 75 leaves no room for doubt: 75 per cent of working mothers have seen their professional career limited because of maternity.
The study indicates that there are many differences regarding the beginning of life in a couple and the number of children, whether the woman works or not and the type of employment she is employed.
Those who do not have an activity outside the home, work part-time or have an unsteady job, get married earlier, have their first pregnancy earlier, and have more children.
On the other hand, women with stable employment, mainly in the public sector, push back entry into life as a couple and first pregnancy, and have fewer children.
Women between the ages of 35 and 49 with fixed employment have their first child, on average, 3.7 years after moving into a couple. This figure increases to 4.1 in those working in the public sector."These data show that women with stable employment have needed more time in their lives to achieve it, which has led them to push back the union and arrival of children.
In addition, the type of employment performed has a significant impact on motherhood, but less on the date of the beginning of common life," explains CSIC researcher Margarita Delgado.
The level of education is another factor that widens the gap between the age of marriage of women and their first child.
According to the survey, the higher the level of training, the more they get married and have their first child late.
The difference is also maintained among women of the same generation.
For example, in the 35-49 age group, those with elementary and higher education were mothers for the first time at 25.1 and at 32.1 years on average, respectively.
"Another distinction also appears among women, depending on their level of education.
While those who have completed elementary education marry and have their first child before finding a stable job, those who have completed middle or higher education reverse this program and give priority to obtaining stable work as a prerequisite for marriage and the arrival of a child," says Delgado.
