The sale of light commercial vehicles is progressing
After almost two years, the light commercial vehicle market began to see some light at the end of the tunnel.
The 9,425 vehicles registered in Spain in November represent an increase of 12.6% compared to 2008 and, more importantly, they represent the first increase after 22 consecutive months of decrease, according to the figures of the employer's union of manufacturers Anfac and Ganvam, that of dealers.
However, the good news should be nuanced, since the comparison reference in November 2008 was particularly poor, with a 60% decrease from the previous year.
As a result, despite the rebound of last month, the registrations accumulated during these 11 months are 40% lower than in the previous fiscal year.
Since January, if you add all vehicles that fall into the category of light commercial vehicles (derived from passenger cars, pick-up trucks, vans, light vans and light chassis trucks) 95 853 have been sold.
The large clouds that affect their demand the most have not dissipated. Indeed, although they are also purchased by individuals, most purchases are made by small or medium-sized enterprises, which pay in almost 100% of the cases through external financing.
Thus, in addition to the restrictions involved in limiting bank loans, other factors must be added, such as the increase in the unemployment rate or the persistence of the bad economic situation.
In view of this situation and the difference between passenger vehicles, the 2000E purchase aid has served little.
